{
  "text": "The final question is why the amplitude of tremor was increased by co-contraction in both cerebellar patients and in normal subjects during repetitive TMS. One possibility is that adjustments to the position of the limb in patients or perturbations due to the repetitive TMS in normal subjects lead to reflex corrective adjustments that require predictive bursts of stabilizing EMG activity [CITATION_1] . If these bursts are reduced or absent then stretch reflexes may occur that reinforce the tremor rather than compensate for it. It is thought that the gain of stretch reflexes is enhanced by cocontraction [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . If so, then perhaps the higher the co-contraction, the larger the stretch reflexes, and the more they reinforce any tremor in the absence of cerebellar predictive activity.",
